  "prompt": "Is there a way to for my Google Calendar to manage my Office 365 Exchange Cal that doesn't involve using the Subscribe Option?",
  "response": "Yes, you can manage your Office 365 Exchange Calendar in Google Calendar without using the Subscribe option by using the following methods:\n\n1. **Importing Events**:\n   - You can export your Office 365 calendar and import it into Google Calendar. However, note that this is a one-time synchronization and won\u2019t update automatically.\n     - In Outlook (Office 365), export your calendar to an .ics file.\n     - In Google Calendar, go to **Settings** > **Import & Export**, then upload the .ics file. \n\n2. **Using Microsoft Power Automate**:\n   - If you're familiar with Microsoft Power Automate (previously Microsoft Flow), you can create a flow that syncs events between your Office 365 Calendar and Google Calendar.\n   - You\u2019ll need to set triggers and actions that suit your workflow, effectively allowing for real-time synchronization depending on how the flow is set up.\n\n3. **Third-Party Integration Tools**:\n   - Consider using third-party applications like Zapier or Automate.io that can create automated workflows. You can set these up to sync events from Office 365 to Google Calendar and vice versa. \n\n4. **Using Office 365 App on Your Phone**: \n   - If you have a mobile device, you can install the Office 365 Outlook app and set it up to access both your Office 365 and Google accounts. This way, you can manage appointments from both services in one app.\n\n5. **Manual Synchronization**:\n   - If all else fails, you can manually add events to both calendars as needed. This is the least efficient method but is always an option.\n\nEach of these methods has its pros and cons, so the best choice will depend on your specific needs regarding updates, accuracy, and ease of management.",
